Rat snakes are literally so goofy and I love them. That is all. *** Answering a bunch of questions, I had no idea this video would blow up so I’m going to do my best! PLEASE don’t pick up snakes if you’re not 100% positive on identification. If you’re interested in learning more about snakes, go visit your local nature center and talk to a naturalist. Or check out your regions conservation snake guide which you can find online. The “growling” sound is just his tail vibrating against my hand, venomous AND non venomous snakes all around the globe will shake their tails as a defense mechanism. The sound/visual effects can warn off predators. Rat snakes will kink up their bodies in order to help them blend in better with their surroundings (think camouflage)… that’s why he looks so squiggly in the beginning. I work at a state park, this individual was clearly in the road and I didn’t want him to get hit. So I relocated him directly across the road. All species of snakes vary in their behaviors, but there are no aggressive snakes in my country, only defensive. POISON IVY! Relax. If you observe the video you’ll notice I decided not to put him down where I was initially going to, because there was too much poison ivy. The second location had less and I didn’t touch it. :3 I live in Missouri and it’s everywhere! Although I’ve come into contact with poison ivy many times, it has never affected me so I’m likely not allergic to it.👌🏼 #ratsnake #missouri #missourisnakes #snakesofmissouri #missouriherping #westernblackratsnake #missouriwildlife @nationalparkservice @natgeo @abcnews @abcworldnewstonight @kfvs @msnbc @bbcnews @newscientist @cnn @bbcnews @themorningshow @cbsnews @discovery @robertirwinphotography

5 knife skills tips that will help you in the kitchen 🔪 Follow @kellyscleankitchen for more in her Basics of Cooking series and comment what you want to see next! It is SO important to have a good foundation in the kitchen when it comes to cooking so that you are safe, efficient, and doing the proper techniques. The most important thing to master first is knife skills! Here are five tips to help you improve on your knife skills! 1. Hold the knife with your pointer finger and thumb on the base of the blade, and the rest of your hand on the handle. This gives you the most control over the knife, and is better for your wrist / hand. 2. Use the bear claw technique with your opposite hand. This is where you grip the produce with your fingertips, but bring your knuckles forward so they are over your fingertips and act as a guard from the knife. This will prevent you from cutting off a fingertip (trust me, I am speaking from experience here)! 3. The best way to cut a bell pepper is by slicing off the stem end, then working your way around the seed pod, cutting through the ribs so it leaves you with the seeds in the middle that you can easily discard and not have a mess of them all over your cutting board. From there, slice and dice the bell pepper as you wish, skin side down for easier cutting. 4. How to dice an onion - slice off the non root side and then through the root slicing in half. Remove the peel. Make horizontal cuts / planks up the onion to the root, but not through it. Turn it to face you and then slice rows vertically down to the board, but not through the root. Turn it away from you again, and slice vertical rows down for the final cut for perfect dices. 5. How to dice a tomato with zero mess - slice the tomato into quarters through the root. Working your way above the skin / flesh of the tomato and under the seeds, remove the seeds and the root. Slice into rows and dices from there. (This is for if you dont want to use the seeds!) What knife skills tips and tricks would you add to this list? #knifeskills #cooking #cooking101

Once you’ve dropped off in one of garment collecting boxes, their business partner takes over.
